[[Image:Sefautaki.jpg|thumb|Sefa-utaki]] {{Nihongo|'''Seifa-utaki'''|斎場御嶽}}, meaning "purified place of Utaki,"<ref>Yamakage, Motohisa ''et al.'' (2006). [http://books.google.com/books?id=cfS8RWn3y58C&pg=PA69&dq=Seifa-utaki&client=firefox-a ''The essence of Shinto,'' p. 69.]</ref> is part of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]] "Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryūkyū" in [[Nanjō, Okinawa|Nanjō]], [[Okinawa]].<ref>Wonder Okinawa: [http://www.wonder-okinawa.jp/002/002/e_riyu.html World Heritage site inclusion]</ref>
Seifa Utaki on Chinen Peninsula has been recognized as a sacred place since the earliest peiod of Okinawan history. The shrine area itself coomprises a number of caves and overhanging ledges opening to the east and south among towering rock formationsof a high promontory over the sea. All buildings have been destroyed, but the outer and inner precincts can still be traced.<ref>Kerr, George H. (1953). [http://books.google.com/books?id=Q5IrAAAAYAAJ&dq=Seifa-utaki&client=firefox-a&output=text&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''Ryukyu Kingdom and Province before 1945,'' p. 10.]</ref>
From July 2007, a local shrine began charging a 200 [[yen]] admission.
