```plaintext {{Source|date=January 14, 2014 (Tue) 00:33 (UTC)|sortkey=Okinawa Sefa-utaki}} [[File:Sangui (Triangle Rock) of Sefa-Utaki.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Sefa-utaki, Sangui]] [[File:Kudakajima Island from Sangui of Sefa-Utaki 1.JPG|200px|right|thumb|View of {{ill|Kudaka Island|ja|久高島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kudaka Island|qq=}} from Sangui]] {{Location map|Japan Mapplot|coordinates={{coord|26.173333|127.826667}}|caption=Sefa-utaki|width=256}} '''Sefa-utaki''' (斎場御嶽, '''Sēfa-utaki''')<ref>{{Cite web|title=Location details |publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs |url=https://www.jldb.bunka.go.jp/creator/locations/detail/470100112/ |accessdate=2018-08-13}}</ref> is a {{ill|Historic Site (Japan)|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic Site (Japan)|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic site|qq=}}} located in {{ill|Nanjō, Okinawa|ja|南城市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanjō, Okinawa|qq=}}, {{ill|Chinen, Okinawa|ja|知念|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinen, Okinawa|qq=}} in [[Okinawa Prefecture]]. It is believed to be an {{ill|Utaki|ja|御嶽 (沖縄)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utaki|qq=}} from the period of the [[Ryukyu Kingdom]] under King {{ill|Shō Shin|ja|尚真|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shō Shin|qq=}} (15th-16th century). The term "Sēfa" means "highest Rank," and thus "Sefa-utaki" translates to "the highest sacred site." The formal sacred name is '''Kimi-ga-dake, Nushi-ga-dake-no-ibi''' (君ガ嶽、主ガ嶽ノイビ).
== Facilities and Legends == The site contains multiple places of worship sharing names with locations within [[Shuri Castle]]. In the innermost area, known as Sangui (三庫理), three {{ill|Haisho|ja|拝所|lt=worship sites|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haisho|qq=}} converge. Among them, "Chōnohana (京の華)" is the highest-Ranking site, where it is said that the Ryukyuan creation deity {{ill|Amamikyu|ja|アマミク|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amamikyu|qq=}} descended through a kuba (fan palm) tree.
From Sangui, visitors can view {{ill|Kudaka Island|ja|久高島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kudaka Island|qq=}}, considered the holiest site associated with the kingdom's creation. However, historical documents do not mention this view, as a section of the rock wall collapsed in modern times. Originally, Sangui was enclosed on three sides by rock walls. Since access to the inner Sangui area was prohibited, visitors can no longer access the Kudaka Island viewing point.
== Sefa-utaki during the Ryukyu Kingdom Era == Sefa-utaki was regarded as the highest sacred site in the kingdom and was under the administration of the highest-Ranking priestess, the {{ill|Kikoe-ōgimi|ja|聞得大君|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikoe-ōgimi|qq=}}. It was the site of the priestess’s inauguration ceremony known as "Oaraori" (御新下り). In the Ryukyu Kingdom, all utaki were traditionally off-limits to men. At Sefa-utaki, commoners were not permitted beyond the outer gate (Ujōguchi, 御門口), and even the king had to dress in women’s attire to enter beyond the gate.
== Cultural Significance == In December 2000, Sefa-utaki, along with [[Shuri Castle]] and other related sites, was inscribed on the [[UNESCO World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage List]] as part of the "{{ill|Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryukyu|ja|琉球王国のグスク及び関連遺産群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gusuku Sites and Related Properties of the Kingdom of Ryukyu|qq=}}." It is also designated a National {{ill|Historic Site (Japan)|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic Site (Japan)|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic site|qq=}}} and a Prefectural Scenic Spot by Okinawa Prefecture. Additionally, artifacts such as ceramics and magatama beads unearthed at Sefa-utaki have been designated as National {{ill|Important Cultural Properties of Japan|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Cultural Properties of Japan|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Cultural Property (Japan)|qq=}} (archaeological materials).
The surrounding forest is considered one of the finest in southern Okinawa Island, with rare species of {{ill|Ferns|ja|シダ植物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ferns|qq=}} and {{ill|Orchidaceae|ja|ラン科|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Orchidaceae|qq=}}. Although most of southern Okinawa was devastated during [[World War II]], this area escaped major destruction. However, several naval artillery shell impact craters are visible, including one along the visitor path. Since the 2000s, conservation work has been undertaken, but signs of forest degradation have appeared.
== As a Tourist Site == {{stub-section|date=February 2025}} Since July 1, 2007, an admission fee has been charged for visitors.
== Issues and Challenges == With a significant increase in visitors, issues such as the wearing down of the stone-paved paths and tourists photographing local worshippers without permission have arisen. In response, {{ill|Nanjō, Okinawa|ja|南城市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanjō, Okinawa|qq=}} authorities are considering reinstating a male-entry prohibition to protect the cultural heritage.<ref>{{Cite news|title="Reinforcing male-entry prohibition considered for UNESCO World Heritage Site Sefa-utaki"|publisher=[[Sankei Shimbun]]|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/politics/news/130920/lcl13092020290001-n1.htm |date=2013-09-20|archive-url=https://archive.is/6BHI0|archive-date=2014-01-14}}</ref>
On April 5, 2021, Nanjō City reported the disappearance of one of the 15 incense burners (kōro, 香炉) from the site, which was replaced by a different stone. The perpetrator was later arrested for {{ill|Theft (crime)|ja|窃盗罪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Theft (crime)|qq=}}, and the stolen item was recovered. However, due to this incident, access to the Sangui area was restricted.<ref>{{Cite web|title="Possible theft at Okinawa World Heritage Sefa-utaki: Incense burner replaced by another stone"|publisher=[[Ryukyu Shimpo]]|url=https://ryukyushimpo.jp/news/entry-1299383.html|accessdate=2021-04-07|date=2021-04-06}}</ref>
